    POST /runtime/process-instances/{processInstanceId}/variables

    This endpoint can be used in 2 ways: By passing a JSON Body (RestVariable or an array of RestVariable) or by passing a multipart/form-data Object. Nonexistent variables are created on the process-instance and existing ones are overridden without any error. Any number of variables can be passed into the request body array. Note that scope is ignored, only local variables can be set in a process instance.

    Body parameter

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    name: myVariable
type: string
value: test
valueUrl: 'http://....'
scope: string

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    processInstanceId path string true No description
    body body RestVariable false No description

    Example responses

    {}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK successful operation object
    201 Created Indicates the process instance was found and variable is created. None
    400 Bad Request Indicates the request body is incomplete or contains illegal values. The status description contains additional information about the error. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested process instance was not found. None
    409 Conflict Indicates the process instance was found but already contains a variable with the given name (only thrown when POST method is used). Use the update-method instead. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    Update a multiple/single (non)binary variable on a process instance

    Code samples

    # You can also use wget
curl -X PUT http://localhost:8080/flowable-rest/service/runtime/process-instances/{processInstanceId}/variables \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -H 'Accept: application/json'


    PUT http://localhost:8080/flowable-rest/service/runtime/process-instances/{processInstanceId}/variables HTTP/1.1

    PUT /runtime/process-instances/{processInstanceId}/variables

    This endpoint can be used in 2 ways: By passing a JSON Body (RestVariable or an array of RestVariable) or by passing a multipart/form-data Object. Nonexistent variables are created on the process-instance and existing ones are overridden without any error. Any number of variables can be passed into the request body array. Note that scope is ignored, only local variables can be set in a process instance.

    Body parameter

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    name: myVariable
type: string
value: test
valueUrl: 'http://....'
scope: string

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    processInstanceId path string true No description
    body body RestVariable false No description

    Example responses

    {}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK successful operation object
    201 Created Indicates the process instance was found and variable is created. None
    400 Bad Request Indicates the request body is incomplete or contains illegal values. The status description contains additional information about the error. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested process instance was not found. None
    415 Unsupported Media Type Indicates the serializable data contains an object for which no class is present in the JVM running the Flowable engine and therefore cannot be deserialized. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    POST /runtime/signals

    Body parameter

    {
  "signalName": "string",
  "variables": [
    {
      "name": "myVariable",

      "value": "test",

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    body body SignalEventReceivedRequest false No description

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    202 Accepted Indicated signal processing is queued as a job, ready to be executed. None
    204 No Content Indicated signal has been processed and no errors occurred. None
    400 Bad Request Signal not processed. The signal name is missing or variables are used together with async, which is not allowed. Response body contains additional information about the error. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    GET /runtime/tasks

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    name query string false Only return models with the given version.
    nameLike query string false Only return tasks with a name like the given name.
    description query string false Only return tasks with the given description.
    priority query string false Only return tasks with the given priority.
    minimumPriority query string false Only return tasks with a priority greater than the given value.
    maximumPriority query string false Only return tasks with a priority lower than the given value.
    assignee query string false Only return tasks assigned to the given user.
    assigneeLike query string false Only return tasks assigned with an assignee like the given value.
    owner query string false Only return tasks owned by the given user.
    ownerLike query string false Only return tasks assigned with an owner like the given value.
    unassigned query string false Only return tasks that are not assigned to anyone. If false is passed, the value is ignored.
    delegationState query string false Only return tasks that have the given delegation state. Possible values are pending and resolved.
    candidateUser query string false Only return tasks that can be claimed by the given user. This includes both tasks where the user is an explicit candidate for and task that are claimable by a group that the user is a member of.
    candidateGroup query string false Only return tasks that can be claimed by a user in the given group.
    candidateGroups query string false Only return tasks that can be claimed by a user in the given groups. Values split by comma.
    involvedUser query string false Only return tasks in which the given user is involved.
    taskDefinitionKey query string false Only return tasks with the given task definition id.
    taskDefinitionKeyLike query string false Only return tasks with a given task definition id like the given value.
    processInstanceId query string false Only return tasks which are part of the process instance with the given id.
    processInstanceBusinessKey query string false Only return tasks which are part of the process instance with the given business key.
    processInstanceBusinessKeyLike query string false Only return tasks which are part of the process instance which has a business key like the given value.
    processDefinitionId query string false Only return tasks which are part of a process instance which has a process definition with the given id.
    processDefinitionKey query string false Only return tasks which are part of a process instance which has a process definition with the given key.
    processDefinitionKeyLike query string false Only return tasks which are part of a process instance which has a process definition with a key like the given value.
    processDefinitionName query string false Only return tasks which are part of a process instance which has a process definition with the given name.
    processDefinitionNameLike query string false Only return tasks which are part of a process instance which has a process definition with a name like the given value.
    executionId query string false Only return tasks which are part of the execution with the given id.
    createdOn query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are created on the given date.
    createdBefore query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are created before the given date.
    createdAfter query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are created after the given date.
    dueOn query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are due on the given date.
    dueBefore query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are due before the given date.
    dueAfter query string(date-time) false Only return tasks which are due after the given date.
    withoutDueDate query boolean false Only return tasks which don?t have a due date. The property is ignored if the value is false.
    excludeSubTasks query boolean false Only return tasks that are not a subtask of another task.
    active query boolean false If true, only return tasks that are not suspended (either part of a process that is not suspended or not part of a process at all). If false, only tasks that are part of suspended process instances are returned.
    includeTaskLocalVariables query boolean false Indication to include task local variables in the result.
    includeProcessVariables query boolean false Indication to include process variables in the result.
    tenantId query string false Only return tasks with the given tenantId.
    tenantIdLike query string false Only return tasks with a tenantId like the given value.
    withoutTenantId query boolean false If true, only returns tasks without a tenantId set. If false, the withoutTenantId parameter is ignored.
    candidateOrAssigned query string false Select tasks that has been claimed or assigned to user or waiting to claim by user (candidate user or groups).
    category query string false Select tasks with the given category. Note that this is the task category, not the category of the process definition (namespace within the BPMN Xml).

    Example responses

    {
  "data": [
    {
      "id": "8",
      "url": "http://localhost:8182/runtime/tasks/8",
      "owner": "owner",

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the action was executed. None
    400 Bad Request When the body contains an invalid value or when the assignee is missing when the action requires it. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found. None
    409 Conflict Indicates the action cannot be performed due to a conflict. Either the task was updates simultaneously or the task was claimed by another user, in case of the claim action. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    All request values are optional. For example, you can only include the assignee attribute in the request body JSON-object, only updating the assignee of the task, leaving all other fields unaffected. When an attribute is explicitly included and is set to null, the task-value will be updated to null. Example: {"dueDate" : null} will clear the duedate of the task).

    DELETE /runtime/tasks/{taskId}

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    cascadeHistory query string false Whether or not to delete the HistoricTask instance when deleting the task (if applicable). If not provided, this value defaults to false.
    deleteReason query string false Reason why the task is deleted. This value is ignored when cascadeHistory is true.

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    204 No Content Indicates the task was found and has been deleted. Response-body is intentionally empty. None
    403 Forbidden Indicates the requested task cannot be deleted because it?s part of a workflow. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    POST /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables

    This endpoint can be used in 2 ways: By passing a JSON Body (RestVariable or an Array of RestVariable) or by passing a multipart/form-data Object. It's possible to create simple (non-binary) variable or list of variables or new binary variable Any number of variables can be passed into the request body array.

    Body parameter

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    name: myVariable
type: string
value: test
valueUrl: 'http://....'
scope: string

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    body body RestVariable false Create a variable on a task

    Example responses

    {}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK successful operation object
    201 Created Indicates the variables were created and the result is returned. None
    400 Bad Request Indicates the name of a variable to create was missing or that an attempt is done to create a variable on a standalone task (without a process associated) with scope global or an empty array of variables was included in the request or request did not contain an array of variables. Status message provides additional information. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found. None
    409 Conflict Indicates the task already has a variable with the given name. Use the PUT method to update the task variable instead. None
    415 Unsupported Media Type Indicates the serializable data contains an object for which no class is present in the JVM running the Flowable engine and therefore cannot be deserialized. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    POST /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/attachments

    This endpoint can be used in 2 ways: By passing a JSON Body (AttachmentRequest) to link an external resource or by passing a multipart/form-data Object to attach a file.

    Body parameter

    {
  "name": "SimpleAttachment.doc",
  "description": "This a simple attachment description",
  "type": "mySimpleType",
  "externalUrl": "http://www.flowable.org"
}

    name: SimpleAttachment.doc
description: This a simple attachment description
type: mySimpleType
externalUrl: 'http://www.flowable.org'

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    body body AttachmentRequest false No description

    Example responses

    {
  "id": "string",
  "url": "string",
  "name": "string",
  "userId": "string",
  "description": "string",
  "type": "string",
  "taskUrl": "string",
  "processInstanceUrl": "string",
  "externalUrl": "string",
  "contentUrl": "string",
  "time": "2017-11-21T09:05:13Z"
}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK successful operation AttachmentResponse
    201 Created Indicates the attachment was created and the result is returned. None
    400 Bad Request Indicates the attachment name is missing from the request. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    GET /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/attachments/{attachmentId}/content

    The response body contains the binary content. By default, the content-type of the response is set to application/octet-stream unless the attachment type contains a valid Content-type.

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    attachmentId path string true No description

    Example responses

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the task and attachment was found and the requested content is returned. Inline
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found or the task doesn?t have an attachment with the given id or the attachment doesn?t have a binary stream available. Status message provides additional information. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    GET /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    scope query string false Scope of variable to be returned. When local, only task-local variable value is returned. When global, only variable value from the task?s parent execution-hierarchy are returned. When the parameter is omitted, a local variable will be returned if it exists, otherwise a global variable.

    Example responses

    [
  {
    "name": "myVariable",
    "type": "string",
    "value": "test",
    "valueUrl": "http://....",
    "scope": "string"
  }
]

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the task was found and the requested variables are returned Inline
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found.. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    GET /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables/{variableName}

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    variableName path string true No description
    scope query string false Scope of variable to be returned. When local, only task-local variable value is returned. When global, only variable value from the task?s parent execution-hierarchy are returned. When the parameter is omitted, a local variable will be returned if it exists, otherwise a global variable.

    Example responses

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the task was found and the requested variables are returned. RestVariable
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found or the task doesn?t have a variable with the given name (in the given scope). Status message provides additional information. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    PUT /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables/{variableName}

    This endpoint can be used in 2 ways: By passing a JSON Body (RestVariable) or by passing a multipart/form-data Object. It's possible to update simple (non-binary) variable or binary variable Any number of variables can be passed into the request body array.

    Body parameter

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    name: myVariable
type: string
value: test
valueUrl: 'http://....'
scope: string

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    variableName path string true No description
    body body RestVariable false Update a task variable

    Example responses

    {
  "name": "myVariable",
  "type": "string",
  "value": "test",
  "valueUrl": "http://....",
  "scope": "string"
}

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the variables was updated and the result is returned. RestVariable
    400 Bad Request Indicates the name of a variable to update was missing or that an attempt is done to update a variable on a standalone task (without a process associated) with scope global. Status message provides additional information. None
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found or the task doesn?t have a variable with the given name in the given scope. Status message contains additional information about the error. None
    415 Unsupported Media Type Indicates the serializable data contains an object for which no class is present in the JVM running the Flowable engine and therefore cannot be deserialized. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    DELETE /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables/{variableName}

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description

    variableName path string true No description
    scope query string false Scope of variable to be returned. When local, only task-local variable value is returned.     To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.

    GET /runtime/tasks/{taskId}/variables/{variableName}/data

    The response body contains the binary value of the variable. When the variable is of type binary, the content-type of the response is set to application/octet-stream, regardless of the content of the variable or the request accept-type header. In case of serializable, application/x-java-serialized-object is used as content-type.

    Parameters

    Parameter In Type Required Description
    taskId path string true No description
    variableName path string true No description
    scope query string false Scope of variable to be returned. When local, only task-local variable value is returned. When global, only variable value from the task?s parent execution-hierarchy are returned. When the parameter is omitted, a local variable will be returned if it exists, otherwise a global variable.

    Example responses

    [
  "string"
]

    Responses

    Status Meaning Description Schema
    200 OK Indicates the task was found and the requested variables are returned. Inline
    404 Not Found Indicates the requested task was not found or the task doesn?t have a variable with the given name (in the given scope). Status message provides additional information. None
    To perform this operation, you must be authenticated.
